text: Before watching the third movie, I was a big fan of The Hobbit. To begin with, LOTR is my bible and the movies are absolutely the best ever made. There can't be a better movie than LOTR.  The first two Hobbit movies were really enjoyable. Sure there are some flaws only LOTR is flawless after all. Everything was going so well. The tention was building thorought Unexpected journej and Desolation of Smaug. The beginning of Battle of the five armies was also superb. But after they killed the dragon in went downside so fast that it ended in the bottom of the ocean. So much hacking and slashing and no story at all. Elf/dwarf romance was silly as hell. And suddenly the movie became a 3d game. Legolas was deffinately playing God of war, controlling trolls with the joyst.... ahem sword. Flying with bads like Kratos with Harpies, I mean come on. This movie was never supposed to be about how many orks can you kill in ridiculuous ways. It became a parody. I didn't even cared about anyone in the end. I cryed my eyes in LOTR several times in sad scenes like Boromir death, here it all seems lame and like a video game.  Now I fully agree with Cristopher Tolkien that Jackson shouldn't be allowed to ruin Silmarillion and make it a CGI orc slaughter movie. I personally would give such a difficult project to Chris Nolan. You need to bond with the characters and to make a believable action scenes just like in LOTR.

text: A review of the film I did for my forum -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  The latest hobbit film is utterly ridiculous! It is rife with ludicrous and deeply embarrassing overacting,¬† laboured pontification, and a torrent of mindless slashing, all delivered in over zealous CGI. The actors declaimed as though on a stage in an auditorium, but perhaps they were desperate to gain the audience's attention because they knew they would be fighting for attention with the CGI action which was made less for being so grandiose and arbitrary. Only a rather charming female elf seemed remotely engaged with the real world and her diary was filled to the brim with casually decapitating orcs, being rescued and sobbing, leaving little time for anything else.  http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/49/EvangelineLillyAsTauriel.jpg/220px-EvangelineLillyAsTauriel.jpg  The film was just downright childish, simplistic and bombastic.  Much of the film was an extended battle scene between "five armies" that was chaotic, confused and meaningless with the highlight being a fashion statement by an elven army that thought it was on parade, a fashion parade. The elves had the shiniest, gaudiest and best polished armour that seemed designed to light up the battlefield and set new standards of Middle Earth couture. The Elves' idea of fighting seemed to be posing and dancing; they pirouetted and pranced about in a staged choreography that they must have practised day and night because never a foot or spear was out of place in a faultlessly synchronised display.  The director, Peter Jackson, appears to be incapable of delivering credible¬† characters or narrative. His characters are simply immature; they were schoolchildren playing at being adults and almost all the actors seem to have been instructed to add dramatic weight to their delivery by constantly shouting or grimacing in a failing struggle for gravitas which made them look silly .  The only redeeming features were the girly elf and the rather charming underlying theme of the virtue of English manners and understatement, exemplified by the diffident character of Bilbo who would interject some of the melodramatic and bombastic declamations by other characters with a timid comment, usually a plea for everyone to get along, calm down and be nice. Oddly, the dragon, despite being a sadistic genocidal creature who delivered the most spine chilling moments and most credibility to a character, managed to bring a touch of decorum to proceedings with his perfect diction and grammar.  The film attempted to depict some human frailty, well dwarven frailty, in the corrosive effect on the mind of power and wealth; judgement and empathy were suggested as immediate victims along with general mental well being, but¬† it failed horribly. The script was hopelessly inept and ponderous as it tackled these themes and struggled to offer anything more than might be expected of an ill-read¬† teenager forced to consider the subject.  The end of the battle was particularly silly. The elves, having put on a fashion show, retired to clean their armour for the next performance, the dwarves were hacked to a standstill by orcs who had a clever plan, apparently, for some of them to retreat just as they were on the verge of victory, when suddenly the battlefield was overtaken by hordes of huge eagles who could transform into killer bears. They came from absolutely nowhere and without any narrative justification whatsoever, but nonetheless they had a firm idea of their role and slashed away at the remaining orcs. A brief shot of a character on a sleigh who had rescued Gandalf in an early part of the film suggested he was controlling the aerial army, but he could have been a birdwatcher for all the narrative sense his appearance made. It was weirdly arbitrary; as though the director had got bored with hours of battle scenes and turned to the last page of the script, leaving all of the intervening storyline unrendered. The remaining orcs were dispensed in a moment and the backup orc army disappeared and suddenly Bilbo and Gandalf waved their goodbyes after some mutual compliments and set some of the narrative elements for Lord of the Rings.  5/10  Oddly, despite it being littered with flaws, ridiculously immature characterisation, and an inept script, I was entertained. It was so bad it was good in some ways and I don't resent having seen it, and of course there was the elven girly and the fabulously cultured dragon.

text: I have watched the movie and in my opinion, it is not a bad movie or a good movie. It is an average movie. The 1 &2 movie followed the book closely (not perfectly) but it is in the 3e that the book and the movie become 2 separate thing. (SPOILER) (SPOILER)  (SPOILER)  The battle become the focus of the movie for about 1h45 of the full 2h24 minutes when it was barely 5 pages in the book. Lots of thing were added, some good like the participation of legolas who link the movies, other were just stranges, like the bats and the second army that serve almost no purpose in the movie. The editing was strange, the movie would cut in the middle of an encounter between protagonist to another group of people far away for no apparent reason,etc. The battle last far too long, it is approximately an 1hour long, after 45 minutes of seeing people kill each other and constant rise in stake, it become more tedious than inspiring. It wasn't bad but some choices made were out of place or not needed.  This is all my opinion, what do you think? Was it a good movie, a bad movie or something in between?

As for the movie itself, it was very... meh. Dildo Baggins and Gandalf are the only characters I came to like. Everything was just drama, explosions, millions of arrows, more explosions, important fight scene that involves the good guy being saved by another good guy, more drama, and then, before I knew what was happening, the movie ended with a boring "returning home" scene.  Seriously though. LOTR needs some comic relief and more interesting characters. Every single character besides Baggins and Gandalf were drama queens.

There are film rating guide lines and regulations that I know filmmakers must follow in order to keep the rating they desire upheld to their film and that lead me to believe that was why only Orcs were be headed and not humans which seemed dark but the humans weren't which took me out of it a bit. Whenever a human or "light" character would be killed they would be saved or some type of "Dues ex Machina" would happen to keep them alive. In relation to that I noticed some scenes had a ton of effort for conveniences. An example would be the hobbit in barrels knocking/defeating all the like 15 Orcs away while staying alive.  There were times where the movie wanted to be dark, then funny, then slap stick and dark again. But only horrific and brutal with chopping heads of the "bad guys" not the protagonist or "heavenly like" character like Legolas.  Legolas is annoying invincible and flawless and still wants to be Fred Flint stone whenever he can. When Woody from 'Toy Story' declared "falling with style" Legolas perfectly fits that phrase. This guy is untouchable to the pint where I want him to loose some and I shouldn't feel that way. He even took Rey Mysterio's wrestling love using his legs to clamp down on an Orcs neck and swing himself across to take the Orc down. I was like that's WWF üòÆüòë lol, I liked it a lil bit. This lead me to enjoy when the Head Orc beat him or "roughed him up some" and made him "bleed his own blood" ha ha haaaaaaaa..... ¬†That's goes with other characters too that unreasonably beat and over powered these strong Orcs with brute physical force with thin brittle arms (That lady Elf who had "the hots" for the one elf who almost "took an arrow to the knee" and had Legolas salty and jelly).  There were some funny moments and I liked some of them. I could see the film was about friendship, trust, journey ¬†and acceptance while conflicting with greed, race war, and power.¬†  I really liked the boss scene at the end which caught me off guard for a bit. It was recalling good.  Overall I could nit-pick the film a lot and point out a ton of minor things that would make sense for the individual characters motives but I liked it. To counter argue the plausibility of characters not doing what would make sense is to keep the suspense going because if they didn't then the story may not be that compelling or thrilling in tense moments, like when the lead hobbit could've slice the head orcs neck when he was behind him as they were looking at the Eagles. It's all for the sake of Storting telling and I keep that in mind as well.

text: I finally saw the film, (spoilers here, so if you have not seen the film then read on at your own risk!) I would say Peter entertained me 68.5% of the time, saw the 3D version, which also added a touch of wonder here and there but was not used to full impact. There were sections that followed closely with the movie that were well done, sections that were made up that were OK and areas that could have been better. I did particularly enjoy the Dol Guldur sequence with the White Council battling Sauron and the Nazgul (taken from the LOTR ROTK appendices).¬† I personally did not like the way Thranduil was portrayed in this one, he still came off as pompous and self centered, although he did attack the mountain with his army in the books, his intentions and his personality were noble in nature, maybe a bit more rustic compared to Elrond, but admirable. I also felt like the battle scene toward the end of the film did not seem to show the Eagles, Elves, Dwarves and Men winning the fight in any sort of detail, it switched focus to the private battles between Azog, Bolg and the Dwarves, (and Tauriel) and when all the 1:1 conflicts were over the big battle seemed to have ended too. I also was hoping to see more Eagles and Beorn in bear form fighting, I suppose those things will be included on the extended version DVD which I am sure will come out around May 2015. Overall we have begun to take Mr. Jackson for granted, and hardcore Tolkien fans are not going to like many of the liberties he and his writers have taken with the plot, this once again is a film interpretation and is aimed at entertaining both fans of the book and those who have never read them, any director who would take on Tolkien's spectacular mythos and is 68% successful has to be commended, if he changed his mind in 5 years and recreated the Silmarillion in some form I would still shell out $15 or so to see it. Even if it was filled with CGI Balrogs, Dragons and Orcs!

text: I know there are those out there that stake their claim as either fans of the movie or fans of the book, but as a true student of Tolkeins works, having been introduced to their literary mastery at a young age... I found the movies to be quite faithful to the book and vastly successful at bringing the world of Tolkein to life.  Tolkein was very strict with his creations and when he sold them, those who obtained them were at first terrified to even approach them. Even Peter Jackson was lost at how to begin tackling the tremendous task of bringing a book to life on the big screen. And while, yes, it does contradict some things in the book, I will go right ahead and defy everyone now who is going to condemn me for saying this.  Tolkein would be proud.   It is hard to speak for a dead man, and even harder to say that I enjoyed the books more than the movie, and was amazed at its imagery and the faithful representations of the characters from the book. Sure some things were off... The size of Durin's Bane, a little comedy sprinkled onto the trolls, etc. and the tiny risks taken with a vast majority of them being hits.  Tolkein knew that there were few who could truly appreciate his work, and I have to say that Jackson is one of the true appreciations for its majesty.   For those of you who hate the movies and spit on any adaption that is not an original Tolkein work, that is fine. But respect those who love Tolkein for another reason, and thank those who read the books after seeing the movies. Thank those who shed tears for Boromir and feared Frodo's death. Thank those who laughed at the lighthearted movie Gollum and the extra scenes created by the hand of the original writer as well as Jackson himself.  We all seem to forget from time to time that no one is Tolkein himself, but there are others besides ourselves who share our deep love of Middle-Earth and all it's people...  When we learn to accept that... I believe we will be better for it, and be one step closer to understanding the true genius of Tolkeins creations, and those clever and brave enough to take up the pen he left for them.  Middle-Earth will never be forgotten... And it will be us to carry on its legend to our children, and our children's children. Our adventures with the Hobbits of Bag-End on their great journeys through the kingdoms of elves, dwarves, and men alike.

text: I'm so tired of people saying how bad Peter messed up the Hobbit films etc. I just read the book. I think it's a very good read if you want to enjoy Middle-Earth again like me. But it is mainly for children. Some characters didn't even have personalities, for ex. the dwarves. Only Thorin but he was also pretty shallow. Some scenes were so short (like their visit to Elrond in the first part) that to put that in a film would be ridiculous. Bringing back Azog is also not a bad idea. Bringing in Sauron (since there is a mention in the book that Gandalf took care of him) it is not a bad idea. Bringing in Tauriel is not a bad idea since there were no female characters in the story. And it is also interesting that Peter basically switched Bard's and Thranduil's behaviour towards the dwarves. In the book Thranduil didn't rush the war. Bard was the more hostile one. But my only problem with this third part is the ending. SPOILER: I think Peter should have shortened the fight scenes and given a proper burial to all the dwarves that had fallen. And also a scene where Dain (like in the book) gives everyone their share of the treasure. Even to Thranduil. I would have enjoyed it very much...Oh and maybe Beorn should have had a bigger role in the battle. Since in the book he killed Bolg.

text: This is a pretty impressive trailer. Seeing it for the first time, and I watched the movie on Xmas day. Unfortunately, it was a pretty huge let down. ¬†Overly long sub plots that lead nowhere, inconsistent characterization, and distractingly bad continuity. By my count, the ragtag army of humans seemed to have more people at the end of the film than it did at the beginning, and this was after taking heaving losses from the battles. I'm exaggerating a bit, but seriously, this movie played like it was for children. Having grown up on the original LOTR Trilogy, I had very high hopes for these films ... just disappointing. Some bright spots here and there, but overall, a massive step back from the original.

text: I can appreciate the three Hobbit movies (and LOTR movies, since they took a few liberties of their own) as their own thing. They don't follow the timeline 100% and they stray from the original path, adding characters/storylines, etc, etc. And that's fine with me. As a fan of both the books and the lore of Middle-earth, I am fine with it being different. So long as the movies were enjoyable (and they were, for the most part), I am perfectly fine with it. And if Tolkien were still with us, I'm sure he'd be okay with it, too.

text: I would like to thank mr. J.R.R. Tolkien for this magnificent fairy tale world he was inspired with and gave to us, in book form it was much worth for sure. I would also like to thank Peter Jackson who achieved, with his amazing, spectacular work, corrections and CANON add-ons on these movies, to have me be entranced, captivated throughout the full length of all three films. The third movie was the most epic part of this masterpiece, for it included joy, wits, friendship, partnership, romance, sorrow, the soul's strength (for Thorin, who managed to defeat his greed, compared to old Thror) and great amusement in general.  The actors, the costume designs, the make-up, the CGI effects, were all remarkable, majestic. I believe every person has his own opinion on anything. We can not have common tastes after all. Just stop arguing and blaming Mr. Jackson, a person who put so much effort in bringing the Universe of the Hobbit in life, like he did with LOTR, in filming those gigantic blockbusters. And my opinion is, he did great.

text: I really loved the Hobbit trilogy! In my opinion, the movie wouldn't be so deep and entertaining if it was exactly like the book. They did an amazing job to expand the characters' personalities. Character development in the book is almost non-existent and the action isn't great either. If you wanted it to be like the book then you would have EVERYTHING from Bilbo's perspective (so it would be quite one-dimensional) and you wouldn't have scenes like Thorin's touching death scene or the battle at Dol Guldur. Yeah, a few parts were campy but it was never meant to be epic like LOTR.

text: How can there be so much ignorance about this trilogy? First of all, if you have a complaint, make it a valid one, not like "wow, such a short book made into such long movies!" If you didn't know, art makes it possible to stretch one single page of writing to a whole series... but that involves creativity and many other things you're not exactly aware (or capable) of. Secondly, using insults and dirty words all over means you are still around 14 and have no superior reasoning capacities, have a very poor self esteem and many psychological issues. Fact! Also, it's beyond pathetic to give so much time of your life to hating something you don't like. Just get over it! Judging by something so simple as the likes and dislikes bar here, by the web activity of fans, by the hype around the premieres and all events and, ultimately, by the numbers of sold tickets and DVS's, Hobbit haters are definitely a very tiny minority. You don't like this film? Fine! You are perfectly entitled to that... but you can only come across as ridiculous with your silly complaints. No, they didn't 'butcher' Tolkien's work. If you want to call it like that, every movie adaptation does that. That's why it's an 'adaptation'. That's why it's 'based on' a book. You're only showing you have no idea about how art is made, especially how they make the transition from book to film. No, Tolkien isn't rolling in the grave, because he was smart enough to be aware of all the possibilities when he agreed to give away the rights. Also, you're no necromancer to know what he's doing beyond the grave, nor did you meet him while he was alive. And then, Christopher is a bad argument here, because he's a bitter old man looking for massive earnings and biting the hand that feeds. Last but not least, trolls shouldn't bother commenting on this because I don't follow youtube threads. Grow up.

text: Say what you want about Peter Jackson, but his movies got me into all of the Tolkien books. When i was a kid, i saw LOTR for the first time in theaters and was amazed, which prompted me to read the LOTR book which is one of my favorite books. Then when the hobbit came out a few years ago, that made me read the Hobbit which i absolutely loved. From there i've also read much more of Tolkien's work such as the Silmarillion for example.  I understand Jackson added some extra characters that were not in the book (tauriel, pale orc, legolas, etc). But lets face it guys, this is hollywood, they need a love story (tauriel and kili), an antagonist (pale orc), and one of the most beloved characters from LOTR to get fans' attention (legolas).  Say what you want about the movies, i thought they were phenomenal and were definitely worth the money i spent on a movie ticket. Of course i prefer the books, but the movies help me get a better picture in my head of what the landscape/characters look like which helps me in reading the books. And everyone is mad about the CGI orcs in this film, but i think the orcs look so much more badass than in LOTR where it was just guys with terrible makeup jobs. Just my personal opinion, but i love both series. Not to mention that i can't get enough of Gandalf!!!

text: The latest and the last of the three part series of The Hobbit: The Battle Of The Five Armies. I was very disappointed in the first two, which were a real let down compared to the LOR series. This latest is a totally different animal. I'm not sure if directer Peter Jackson took some of the criticisms to heart from the last two movies and made it right, or he'd always planned the last one to make up for the first two, but it does. For lovers of the LOR series (and you'd have to screwed in the brain not to be a fan of those movies frankly...) this latest movie is much closer to them.  The first two Hobbit movies felt directed at kids, suffered CGI overkill, and just left most serous LOR fans flat. This latest movie is much more adult oriented, CGI used to enhance vs dominate as it did for LOR, solid acting, great battle scenes, and Action from start to finish. It does not have the "magic" of LOR, but it's a solid A- movie that almost makes up for those last two duds.

text: To all people who think the Hobbit is the last time you will see Middle Earth on the big screen just remember the English copyright laws state that 70 years (Under the 1995 regulations) after the death of the author the material is free to use. The debate will be if JRR is the true author of the Silmarillion/Lost Tales (The only real way to make more Movies/TV shows). JRR may have written the material but his son Christopher finished and published both works so its up for debate who actually "wrote it". So lets do some math.  If JRR Wrote it: Died in 1973 so its 27 years to 2000 2000+43( The remaining # of years) = The year 2043 (Best Case Scenario)  If Christopher Wrote it: Still alive but 90 years old (lets assume he will die within 5 years, kind of rude I know) 2015,2020 +70 = Between the years of 2085 and 2090 (Worse Case Scenario)  I'm not a legal expert so i'm sure this will be debated endlessly in courts.   But in the end money talks so i'm sure we will be seeing one much sooner after all in the words of JK Rowling¬†  ‚ÄúThere's always room for a story that can transport people to another place.‚Äù

text: Sorry this is so long but I just had to speak my mind...  I don't understand the hate on these movies even through everyone is entitled to their own opinion and I respect that. Stretching them out to three instead of two was the best decesion and you can understand why if you watch all of the behind the scenes in the extended addition (which is absolutely worth the hours upon hours it takes to watch :D).  Two films would not have been enough. Shoot, three barely is if you were to include every detail of the book. I know that is what many of us really want but I understand how hard that is to achieve. However these films I truly believed enhanced the book. I know Peter Jackson added in a lot that was not in the book. However I do not see those things as changes that hurt the story but additions that enhance it and help the viewers (especially ones who have not read the book) piece the story together. When your reading the book your OK with details being left out. But from a filmmakers point of view you can't have those gaps or it hinders the flow of the story. So Peter Jackson and his amazing crew filled it in. Everything they added was not blindly thrown in, it was carefully thought out and investigated by breaking down pieces of the Apendecies and then placed it. Not to mention time had to be added in for the fight sequences which are not elaborated in the book because it is almost impossible to have a written description of the battles. But for a film you need to draw the fights out to add to the energy. Legolas and Tauriel were the biggest debate. For me I loved them (although I am not a very critical person and is almost good with anything). To me they added to the storytelling about the Mirkwood elves and gave you a deeper attachment to Thranduil. Tauriel also provided a strong female presence and her and Killi hinted at the scene with Gimli and Gladriel thus expanding on the complicated relationship with Dwarves and Elves. Also who is to say that there wasn't a character like Tauriel amongst the woodland elves. Having her and Legolas split off to spy on the orc strong hold helped connect why and where this second orc army came from. Her grief over Killi also helped add to the heartbreak.   My ONLY issue is that their was no mourning scene over Fili like there was for his brother and uncle. Fili deserved more tears haha

text: This movie is absolutely horrible. Now, vast majority of the people that have seen this did not read the book, but I did, and you wanna know how long this section of the book was? SIX PAGES, out of a 200 page book. I don't even know why Sauron was in this, he wasn't in the book at all, they made thorin look way more evil than he was, there was no romance between the elves- strike that, the elves didn't have a story at all in the book, and just overall... what the fuck. This is probably the worst trilogy of movies made from a book ever made, which is a shame because the original trilogy of LOTR was almost flawless, and that makes me disappointed. I see all these comments saying "best movie ever" which is just ridiculous.  In the chapter that has the battle, the lake towns people realize that if the dragon is dead they are entitled to the money in the mountain, not knowing the dwarves are still alive. A bunch of stuff happens and in the end the dwarves build a wall to the entrance of the mountain, and the Lake town allied with the elves, and they marched on. When they arrive all three parties discuss the treasure and how it will be distributed blah blah blah. At night Bilbo climbs down from the wall and gives the arkenstone to the humans and elves, to keep everyone from fighting. However, the goblins attack and all out war ensues, and Bilbo is ex communicated due to giving away the arkenstone. After a while the eagles show up, and Bilbo gets hit in the head with a rock and misses the rest of the battle. When he wakes, it's all over.  That's it, about six pages and they made a two and a half hour movie out of it. What scummy cash grab.
